<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area in Real-Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_xzoco4fa">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_vy20pqpz">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_u53900gi">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qe9q1c92">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_4afndizi">
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kbiub01a">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_trgb2jo0">Calculate the volume of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5a53hcb9">Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_az3h5fl0" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ymso7ro7">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4m9dv4sw" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_4lwlebx3">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <introduction xml:id="auto_kzudltqg" component="lesson-plan">
            <p xml:id="auto_qvvmhmoc"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_6gbjuyyw">
                    <p xml:id="auto_df05jp0g">
                        <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Explain how surface area calculations apply to real-life problems involving coverage, cost, and material estimates. Identify which surfaces to include (lateral vs. total) depending on the context. State the importance of unit consistency.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_eoxkqnir">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6x9j5vih">
                        <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Convert between units before computing areas. Apply the correct surface area formula for common shapes (cylinders, rectangular prisms, pyramids, cones, spheres). Determine the number of material units needed and calculate costs.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6r66ud03">
                    <p xml:id="auto_wa6rd897">
                        <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-life problems involving painting, roofing, wrapping, and coating by calculating surface area and linking it to material costs. Decompose complex objects into simpler shapes for calculation.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_qlxwmbae">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/surface-area-in-real-life.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_wnozhfqb">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/step-by-step-guide_surface-area-in-real-life.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_vnvd7x0j">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8257p7qf">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Groups of 2–3
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_v045yzzg">
            <alert>Activity:</alert> Planning to Paint Your House
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_3d60y5n9">
            <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_4c9f4udt"><p xml:id="auto_w6rmpq9g"><q>Is the pillar a cylinder? Is the box a rectangular prism?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_v7470ivw"><p xml:id="auto_ks67d81k"><q>Do you paint the top and bottom of a pillar, or just the curved side?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2dtbu2e1"><p xml:id="auto_xoo7s7dg"><q>If one bucket covers <m>5 \text{ m}^2</m> and your area is <m>3 \text{ m}^2</m>, how many buckets do you buy?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_k7x080ev"><p xml:id="auto_my4v9tpf">Remind students to use consistent units (convert cm to m).</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_69fa7s18">
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_4h607mf6"><p xml:id="auto_4evb69k6">Organise students into groups of 2–3.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_a22r34si"><p xml:id="auto_2tfhqvim">Encourage students to think of familiar objects from their homes.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_cap9gve7"><p xml:id="auto_21s2dram">Guide students to identify shapes: cylinders, rectangular prisms, pyramids, etc.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_q2x1dcnw"><p xml:id="auto_3fs7ipvv">Students should discover: surface area determines material needs and costs.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <introduction xml:id="auto_pyjsc3vu">
        <p xml:id="auto_q6rg5yg5">
            Surface area is a fundamental geometric concept with many practical uses. Engineers use surface area to calculate heat transfer and cooling rates; manufacturers rely on it for coating, painting, or material estimates; architects and landscapers use it when planning cladding, tiling, or irrigation coverage; and scientists use surface area to model reactions that occur at interfaces (e.g., catalysis or evaporation). Understanding how to compute surface area lets you accurately size materials, predict performance, and control costs across a wide range of real-world applications.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <activity xml:id="auto_qzdifxsq">
        <statement>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_3d11oqx3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_mtvq3toq">
                        Think about parts of your house or objects within your house you may want to paint.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_eit30a2q">
                    <p xml:id="auto_k8t0k8wg">
                        For example, this could include pillars, walls, boxes, the roof, ...
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_689pobkk">
                    <p xml:id="auto_be1mvth3">
                        For each, determine what kind of shape it is and estimate its dimensions.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jxe0xy4c">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zsa4g72s">
                        For each, determine whether you would paint the entire object or only parts of it, and determine the surface area that you want to paint.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8sypst1o">
                    <p xml:id="auto_j9kgybkt">
                        If a small bucket of paint costs 500 ksh and is sufficient to cover 5 <m>m^2</m>, how much does it cost to paint the different objects you identified?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </statement>
    </activity>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_il8t7rfz">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_lfh0z887">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Whole class
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qunydno4">
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalise their discoveries. Emphasise unit conversion as a separate explicit step. Use visual diagrams showing which surfaces to include. Provide a formula reference chart for common shapes.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_aag3nwvm">
            <alert>Key Formula Reference:</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Shape</cell>
                <cell>Lateral Surface Area</cell>
                <cell>Total Surface Area</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Cylinder</cell>
                <cell><m>2\pi rh</m></cell>
                <cell><m>2\pi rh + 2\pi r^2</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Rectangular Prism</cell>
                <cell><m>2h(l + w)</m></cell>
                <cell><m>2(lw + lh + wh)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Pyramid</cell>
                <cell>Sum of triangle areas</cell>
                <cell>Lateral + base area</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Cone</cell>
                <cell><m>\pi r\ell</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\pi r\ell + \pi r^2</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Sphere</cell>
                <cell>N/A</cell>
                <cell><m>4\pi r^2</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
        <p xml:id="auto_qwmf5qqp">
            <alert>Prompting Questions:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_sz979u06"><p xml:id="auto_xuw6m4ad"><q>When do we use lateral surface area vs. total surface area?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_64z7j88m"><p xml:id="auto_hhl7qjlm"><q>Why is it important to convert units before calculating?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pm33mkug"><p xml:id="auto_7ol6opn4"><q>How does surface area link to cost?</q></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

     <insight xml:id="auto_1xx0ebcg">
        <p xml:id="auto_mn7gxuni">
            Understanding surface area helps solve practical problems involving coverage, cost and material estimates.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_02a0egzr">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_83fypuqn">
                    <p xml:id="auto_lq21dcn9">
                        Surface area calculations determine how much material is needed to cover an object (paint, fabric, roofing, cladding).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_oltr7qnz">
                    <p xml:id="auto_tfvs7hrg">
                        Always use consistent units before computing areas; convert measurements when necessary.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vcicp364">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ismebrb1">
                        Recognise and apply the correct formula for common shapes (prisms, cylinders, cones, pyramids, spheres) and decompose complex objects into simpler parts.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jpnqvj3i">
                    <p xml:id="auto_qgori9q5">
                        Distinguish between lateral and total surface area depending on whether ends/bases are included in the coverage.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xbuguzwe">
                    <p xml:id="auto_62el06oj">
                        Surface area links directly to cost and planning; accurate calculations reduce waste and help estimate expenses.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_e6al5r2s">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_jtlvtbxf">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual, then pairs to compare
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_mxa4upgx">
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> Walk learners through the worked examples that follow. Emphasise the four-step approach: (1) Standardise units, (2) Identify which surfaces to include, (3) Calculate the area, (4) Determine cost. After the pillar example, have learners attempt the gift box exercise independently.
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <example label="house-pillar-example">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_h14mwz2c">
            We want to paint a round pillar in our house.
            It is 3 meters tall and has a radius of 15 cm.
            If a small bucket of paint costs 500 ksh and is sufficient to cover 5 <m>m^2</m>, how much does it cost to paint the pillar?
        </p> 
       </statement> 
        <solution>
            <paragraphs><title>Standardize the Units</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_3p5glnib">The height is given in meters, but the radius is in centimeters. To make our calculations consistent, we should convert the radius to meters:</p>
                <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_6buut8nz"><em>Height (<m>h</m>):</em> <m>3 \text{ m}</m></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dwav357s"><em>Radius (<m>r</m>):</em> <m>15 \text{ cm} = 0.15 \text{ m}</m></li>
                </ul>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Calculate the Lateral Surface Area</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_df5d9am4">The formula for the curved surface area of a cylinder is <m>A = 2\pi rh</m>. This is essentially the circumference of the circle multiplied by the height.</p>
                <md>
                <mrow>A \amp = 2 \times \pi \times 0.15 \times 3</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = 0.9 \times \pi</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp \approx 0.9 \times 3.14159</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp \approx 2.827 \text{ m}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Determine the Number of Buckets Needed</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_nechlw4f">One bucket of paint covers <m>5 \text{ m}^2</m>. We compare this to the area of our pillar:</p>
                <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_lxswirf7"><em>Area to paint:</em> <m>2.827 \text{ m}^2</m></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_i0abnssj"><em>Bucket coverage:</em> <m>5 \text{ m}^2</m></li>
                </ul>
                <p xml:id="auto_ryicckxp">Since the area of the pillar (<m>2.827 \text{ m}^2</m>) is less than the coverage of one bucket (<m>5 \text{ m}^2</m>), we only need to purchase <em>one bucket</em> of paint.</p>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Calculate the Total Cost</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_99gk9yv5">Even though we won't use the entire bucket, hardware stores typically don't sell half-buckets! Therefore, we must buy one full bucket.</p>

                <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_f94kw1vs"><em>Number of buckets:</em> <m>1</m></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9r0il9h6"><em>Price per bucket:</em> <m>500 \text{ ksh}</m></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_er5ddgxs"><em>Total Cost:</em> <m>1 \times 500 = 500 \text{ ksh}</m></li>
                </ul>
            </paragraphs>
        </solution> 
    </example>

    <example label="house-roof-example">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_xq6getqw">
            For a house whose base is a square of <m>6 \times 6</m> meters
            we want to construct a roof that has a pyramid shape.
            The diagonals from the edge to the top are 5 meters long.
            If a square meter of roofing material costs 2000 ksh,
            how much does the roofing material cost that we need for the house?
        </p>  
        <image width="50%">
            <shortdescription> Roof of a house </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="house-roof-example-image">
                \tdplotsetmaincoords{60}{60}
                \begin{tikzpicture}[tdplot_main_coords]
                % Define Coordinates
                % Base of the house (z = 0)
                \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);
                \coordinate (B) at (8,0,0);
                \coordinate (C) at (8,8,0);
                \coordinate (D) at (0,8,0);
                
                % Top of the walls / Base of the roof (z = 6)
                \coordinate (A1) at (0,0,6);
                \coordinate (B1) at (8,0,6);
                \coordinate (C1) at (8,8,6);
                \coordinate (D1) at (0,8,6);
                
                % Peak of the pyramid roof
                % To have side lengths of 6m with a base of 8m, 
                % the height (h) must be: h = sqrt(6^2 - (sqrt(8^2+8^2)/2)^2) = sqrt(36 - 32) = 2
                \coordinate (Peak) at (4,4,8);

                % --- Draw Back (Hidden) Edges ---
                \draw[dashed, gray] (A) -- (D);
                \draw[dashed, gray] (D) -- (C);
                \draw[dashed, gray] (D) -- (D1);
                
                % --- Draw Base and Walls ---
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C);
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (A1);
                \draw[thick] (B) -- (B1);
                \draw[thick] (C) -- (C1);
                \draw[thick] (A1) -- (B1) -- (C1) -- (D1) -- cycle;
                
                % --- Draw Roof ---
                \draw[thick, fill=blue!10, fill opacity=0.3] (A1) -- (B1) -- (Peak) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick, fill=blue!20, fill opacity=0.3] (B1) -- (C1) -- (Peak) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick, fill=blue!20, fill opacity=0.3] (C1) -- (D1) -- (Peak) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick, fill=blue!20, fill opacity=0.3] (D1) -- (A1) -- (Peak) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick] (A1) -- (Peak);
                \draw[thick] (C1) -- (Peak);

                % --- Labels for Dimensions ---
                % Base Width
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, shift={(0,-0.7,0)}] (A) -- node[below] {6 m} (B);
                
                % Side length of the roof triangle
                % Labeling the edge between B1 and the Peak
                \path (B1) -- (Peak) node[midway, right, xshift=2pt] {5 m};
                \path (C1) -- (Peak) node[midway, right, xshift=2pt] {5 m};

                % Optional: Label the base of the triangle on the roof
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;, blue, shift={(0,0,0.2)}] (B1) -- node[above] {6 m} (C1);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image> 
       </statement> 
        <solution>
        <paragraphs>
            
            <title>Identify the Triangle Dimensions</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_cak2m9pk">Each of the four triangular sides of the roof has the following side lengths:</p>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_odczcrg3"><em>Side <m>a</m>:</em> <m>5 \text{ m}</m></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ckpx8ndr"><em>Side <m>b</m>:</em> <m>5 \text{ m}</m></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3koz4z5v"><em>Side <m>c</m> (Base):</em> <m>6 \text{ m}</m></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Calculate the Area Using Heron's Formula</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_x29dxu36">Heron's Formula allows us to find the area of a triangle when we know all three sides. First, we find the <em>semi-perimeter</em> (<m>s</m>):</p>

            <ul>
            <li xml:id="auto_e30p6sy6"><m>s = \frac{a + b + c}{2} = \frac{5 + 5 + 6}{2} = \frac{16}{2} = 8 \text{ m}</m></li>
            </ul>

            <p xml:id="auto_7s1qlqsv">Now, we use the Area formula:</p>
            <md>
                <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}</mrow>
                <mrow>            \amp = \sqrt{8(8-5)(8-5)(8-6)}</mrow>
                <mrow>            \amp = \sqrt{8 \times 3 \times 3 \times 2}</mrow>
                <mrow>            \amp = \sqrt{144} = 12 \text{ m}^2</mrow>
            </md>
        </paragraphs>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Total Roofing Material Needed</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_ggeespvx">Since the roof has <em>four identical triangles</em>, we multiply the area of one triangle by four:</p>

            <ul>
            <li xml:id="auto_sku3icrv"><em>Total Area:</em> <m>12 \times 4 = 48 \text{ m}^2</m></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Calculate the Total Cost</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_mm9c4t5k">We multiply the total area by the price of <m>2000 \text{ ksh}</m> per square meter:</p>

            <p xml:id="auto_9xcxaid5"><em>Total Cost:</em> <m>48 \times 2000 = 96000 \text{ ksh}</m></p>
        </paragraphs>
        </solution> 
    </example>  

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_8jbow70t">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_he1x0b6k">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_sln1pqsf">
            <alert>Exit Ticket:</alert> Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4sfv3zcs">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_ggm2zy1n">
                    <p xml:id="auto_eqe6hw98">A cylindrical pillar has radius <m>20</m> cm and height <m>4</m> m. Calculate the lateral surface area in <m>\text{m}^2</m>. If paint costs <m>600</m> ksh per bucket and one bucket covers <m>6 \text{ m}^2</m>, how much does it cost to paint the pillar?</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hbapixai">
                    <p xml:id="auto_k7h38gcf">Why is it important to use consistent units when calculating surface area for real-life applications?</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_egopymbf">
                    <p xml:id="auto_wkpx5iag">Explain the difference between lateral surface area and total surface area. Give an example of when you would use each.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vkt9luqz">
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8p59duzt">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_w1i7hyyy">
                    <p xml:id="auto_nsqx1or8">Convert: <m>r = 0.20</m> m. <m>A = 2\pi rh = 2 \times \pi \times 0.20 \times 4 = 1.6\pi \approx 5.03 \text{ m}^2</m>. Buckets: <m>5.03 \div 6 \lt 1</m>, so 1 bucket. Cost: <m>1 \times 600 = 600</m> ksh.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8wit8wj7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_qmp65ksf">Using consistent units prevents calculation errors and ensures accurate material estimates. Mixing cm and m leads to incorrect surface areas, wasting money or causing shortages.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_310uyvcr">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dej8k7hq">Lateral surface area includes only side surfaces (e.g., painting a pillar without top/bottom). Total surface area includes all surfaces including bases (e.g., wrapping a gift box completely).</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-surface-area-real-life">
        <title>Exercises</title>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-leather-ball">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_bv7m3vds">
                    A spherical ball has radius <m>15	\text{ cm}</m>. How much leather is needed to cover the entire surface of the ball? If leather costs <m>1200	\text{ ksh}</m> per square metre, estimate the cost of the leather required.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <m>0.09\pi	\text{ m}^2 	\text{ (approximately }0.283	\text{ m}^2)</m>
            </answer>
            <answer>
                <m>\text{Cost }= 108\pi\text{ ksh (approximately }339.3\text{ ksh)}</m>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_xbti2ach">
                    Convert radius to metres: <m>r = 15	\text{ cm} = 0.15	\text{ m}.</m> Surface area of a sphere is <m>A = 4\pi r^2.</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>A \amp = 4\pi (0.15)^2 = 4\pi(0.0225) = 0.09\pi\text{ m}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp \approx 0.09 \times 3.14159 \approx 0.283\text{ m}^2</mrow>
                </md>
                <p xml:id="auto_jkrfpqot">
                    Cost: <m>0.09\pi \times 1200 = 108\pi\text{ ksh} \approx 339.3\text{ ksh}.</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-gift-wrap-box">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_w1suur4l">
                    A gift box is a rectangular prism with dimensions <m>40	\text{ cm} \times 30	\text{ cm} \times 25	\text{ cm}.</m> How much wrapping paper (in square metres) is required to cover the entire box (including top and bottom)?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <m>0.59	\text{ m}^2</m>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_sta3y36b">
                    Convert dimensions to metres: <m>l=0.40\text{ m},\; w=0.30\text{ m},\; h=0.25\text{ m}.</m> Total surface area of a cuboid is <m>2(lw+lh+wh).</m>
                </p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{SA} \amp = 2(0.40\times0.30 + 0.40\times0.25 + 0.30\times0.25)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 2(0.12 + 0.10 + 0.075) = 2(0.295) = 0.59\text{ m}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

   

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_87v2bfmv">
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_qpdx0gho"><p xml:id="auto_55usygts">Provide formula reference cards.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jibfzk4w"><p xml:id="auto_gnfpfitg">Break calculations into explicit steps: (1) Convert units, (2) Apply formula, (3) Calculate cost.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_b22wu2af"><p xml:id="auto_3w0vmjg5">Use simpler shapes (cylinders, rectangular prisms) initially.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_de8zpb95"><p xml:id="auto_3tpbprdg">Provide worked example templates to follow.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bx4gglz6"><p xml:id="auto_ww0fiud5">Use visual diagrams showing which surfaces to include.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_c5j2rvaa">
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_iopdxtw9"><p xml:id="auto_zilxc1pr">Encourage students to work with different shapes and verify their calculations.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jbj2sxix"><p xml:id="auto_03btt1k3">Provide mixed practice combining different shapes.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ahxtgy6n"><p xml:id="auto_lkvmz8mj">Challenge students to identify which surfaces to include in different contexts.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_q4do1n1x">
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_wh2uvh8u"><p xml:id="auto_pn9bt6er">Challenge with composite solids (multiple shapes combined).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_s8bq7emr"><p xml:id="auto_2q8vyxdj">Introduce optimisation problems (minimise cost while meeting requirements).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_t66o2ytc"><p xml:id="auto_4bxtmbje">Explore irregular shapes requiring decomposition.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dk9o6zlr"><p xml:id="auto_r0pgekxf">Connect to careers: architecture, engineering, manufacturing.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5k90yumq"><p xml:id="auto_q18tz2ug">Calculate waste percentages and efficiency.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Extension Activity</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_8nf1zueq">
            <alert>Real-World Surface Area Investigation</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ag5xx505">
            Work in groups. Choose real-world objects around your school or home and calculate their surface areas.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_u6hmedig">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_w9f5l8kf"><p xml:id="auto_1d06hqpj">Identify at least three objects with different shapes (cylinder, rectangular prism, pyramid, sphere).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pexgyoc2"><p xml:id="auto_ln7h6w37">Measure or estimate the dimensions of each object.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tugy8uoj"><p xml:id="auto_g1ivpzpr">Determine whether to use lateral or total surface area, depending on the context.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_j2hamzv0"><p xml:id="auto_lisxdwgd">Calculate the surface area and the cost of painting/covering each object.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ag46jvkz"><p xml:id="auto_nlo78243">Present your findings with diagrams, measurements, and calculations.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

